WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.460
What if the reason you feel totally overwhelmed by information isn't because your brain is too

00:07.460 --> 00:12.600
full, but because your memory is actually physically missing a dimension?

00:13.520 --> 00:21.900
It's a really profound question. I mean, we're so accustomed to thinking of our minds as

00:21.900 --> 00:25.580
these storage containers with fixed volumes.

00:25.580 --> 00:29.760
Right, exactly. Like a hard drive, you get that awful notification on your phone that says,

00:30.000 --> 00:33.600
storage almost full, please delete some files to continue.

00:33.900 --> 00:34.920
Yeah, we've all seen that.

00:35.000 --> 00:40.000
And we just, like, we apply that exact same logic to ourselves. We assume that to learn

00:40.000 --> 00:44.320
something new, we have to push something old out, or at least compress it.

00:44.380 --> 00:49.020
We do. But today, we're going to challenge that entire framework.

00:49.240 --> 00:54.800
Yes, we are. Welcome to the Deep Dive, everyone. Our mission today is to really unpack this

00:54.800 --> 00:59.920
incredibly dense, genuinely revolutionary, independent research paper.

01:00.080 --> 01:02.860
Right. It's dated April 24, 2026.

01:03.180 --> 01:09.760
Yeah. It's titled Error as Obstruction, authored by a researcher named Flyxion. And I mean,

01:09.820 --> 01:11.400
the scope of this thing is wild.

01:11.400 --> 01:17.560
It really is. The scope cannot be overstated. Flyxion is proposing a fundamental rewriting

01:17.560 --> 01:24.000
of the mathematics of learning, of memory, and, well, of error.

01:24.200 --> 01:27.440
And this applies to everything, right? Not just human cognition.

01:27.800 --> 01:34.080
Exactly. Not just us, but machine learning, artificial intelligence, basically any complex

01:34.080 --> 01:36.580
system that processes historical events.

01:36.580 --> 01:42.020
Okay. So, to set the stage for you listening, we have to talk about what Flyxion calls the

01:42.020 --> 01:43.620
bottleneck assumption.

01:44.400 --> 01:47.000
Uh, yes. The bottleneck assumption.

01:47.340 --> 01:52.800
This is, like, the universally accepted idea that our capacity to represent information is

01:52.800 --> 01:59.180
strictly limited. The assumption is that the raw data of your daily experience, you know,

01:59.240 --> 02:02.240
it vastly exceeds what you can actually retain.

02:02.480 --> 02:04.140
Right. It's the economics of scarcity.

02:04.140 --> 02:10.080
Yeah. So, the conventional wisdom says that to generalize, to actually be smart and not just,

02:10.220 --> 02:14.780
you know, a walking encyclopedia, you must forget. You must compress.

02:15.060 --> 02:17.960
Yeah. And this assumption is deeply baked into everything.

02:18.200 --> 02:23.560
It really is. In evolutionary psychology, we just assume the brain evolved to discard the noise,

02:23.660 --> 02:26.080
right? Keep only the crucial survival signals.

02:26.160 --> 02:26.420
Yeah.

02:26.420 --> 02:32.040
And in computer science, early constraints on RAM and physical storage,

02:32.780 --> 02:37.700
they literally forced programmers to compress data aggressively.

02:37.860 --> 02:38.760
Yeah, they had to.

02:38.980 --> 02:43.680
Exactly. We built our entire philosophy of intelligence around the scarcity.

02:44.360 --> 02:48.260
The bottleneck assumption basically tells us that generalization and memorization

02:48.260 --> 02:51.240
are locked in this zero-sum game.

02:51.240 --> 02:56.780
Okay. Let's unpack this for a second, because if you look at how we operate in the real world,

02:57.220 --> 03:00.240
this assumption dictates literally everything.

03:01.040 --> 03:01.560
Oh, absolutely.

03:01.780 --> 03:04.680
Like, if you're a struggling student, what does your advisor tell you?

03:04.900 --> 03:08.280
Drop a class. You're spreading yourself too thin. Focus your energy.

03:08.420 --> 03:09.240
Right. Like, subtraction.

03:09.980 --> 03:14.300
Exactly. Or, if you're a software engineer and your code base is getting messy, what do you do?

03:14.300 --> 03:19.760
The standard advice is to refactor, reduce the inputs, strip it down.

03:20.160 --> 03:24.140
The solution to cognitive friction is always, always subtraction.

03:24.240 --> 03:31.200
Always. But, Flyxion introduces a counterexample that completely, like, completely disrupts this.

03:31.460 --> 03:33.120
The cross-trained master builder.

03:33.680 --> 03:35.400
Yes. The master builder.

03:35.860 --> 03:40.820
It is an excellent place to start, actually, because it perfectly illustrates what happens

03:40.820 --> 03:44.000
when a system operates outside of that scarcity.

03:44.300 --> 03:48.180
Okay. So, imagine a master builder on a construction site.

03:48.700 --> 03:56.340
This person knows electrical work, plumbing, structural framing, HVAC, finishing work.

03:56.520 --> 04:00.340
They have an immense, highly detailed database of knowledge.

04:00.460 --> 04:01.940
Right. An immense database.

04:02.600 --> 04:08.840
So, when that builder looks down and sees, I don't know, a random scrap piece of copper wire on the floor,

04:08.840 --> 04:11.820
they aren't hit with cognitive overload.

04:12.120 --> 04:13.100
No. Not at all.

04:13.160 --> 04:16.180
They aren't paralyzed because they know too much about construction.

04:16.660 --> 04:22.700
Precisely. I mean, the novice, like the apprentice who maybe only knows basic framing,

04:23.420 --> 04:26.460
they look at the wire and just see a disconnected object.

04:26.560 --> 04:28.220
Right. They might just step right over it.

04:28.300 --> 04:31.400
Exactly. But the master builder processes it instantly.

04:31.400 --> 04:36.400
Yeah. In a fraction of a second, that single piece of wire is automatically indexed.

04:37.120 --> 04:46.340
By its function, its potential as a safety hazard, its exact reuse potential for a specific electrical run they're doing tomorrow.

04:46.500 --> 04:48.260
And its sequence in the overall build.

04:48.560 --> 04:54.100
Exactly. Adding more structured experience didn't increase the builder's cognitive burden.

04:54.480 --> 05:00.200
It actually made understanding that random piece of wire completely effortless.

05:00.200 --> 05:09.260
And that is because the builder is operating in what Flyxion defines mathematically as a state of excess capacity.

05:09.900 --> 05:12.140
Excess capacity. I love that term.

05:12.400 --> 05:18.140
Right. The old subtraction prescription, it feels intuitive when a system is constrained.

05:18.900 --> 05:21.740
When it's struggling just to fit the basic facts together.

05:21.860 --> 05:23.560
Yeah, like the struggling student.

05:23.960 --> 05:29.640
But when a system achieves excess capacity, more knowledge doesn't crowd the room.

05:29.640 --> 05:33.380
It actually provides the scaffolding to organize the room more efficiently.

05:33.740 --> 05:36.620
But wait, I'm trying to map this to my own experience.

05:37.200 --> 05:43.120
And, I mean, cognitive overload is a very real biological sensation.

05:43.260 --> 05:44.920
Oh, absolutely. It's not a myth.

05:45.040 --> 05:49.660
Like, if I sit down and try to read five dense academic papers in a row,

05:50.040 --> 05:53.180
my brain physically feels like it's grinding to a halt.

05:53.180 --> 05:55.520
The too-many-tabs-open feeling is real.

05:55.860 --> 06:01.520
So how can adding more structured experience to that situation actually reduce my burden?

06:01.880 --> 06:04.280
Well, it is a necessary pushback.

06:04.960 --> 06:06.720
I mean, the fatigue you feel is real.

06:07.200 --> 06:10.880
But Flyxion argues we are completely misdiagnosing the cause.

06:11.320 --> 06:13.940
Really? Misdiagnosing how?

06:13.940 --> 06:20.260
You are feeling the friction of trying to force new data into a low-dimensional space.

06:20.620 --> 06:25.060
We basically have to completely discard the container metaphor of learning.

06:25.400 --> 06:29.100
Okay, so I'm not filling a bucket with water until it spills over.

06:29.300 --> 06:31.360
No. Learning is a geometry.

06:32.220 --> 06:36.880
As you accumulate interconnected knowledge, you aren't using up-limited megabytes.

06:36.980 --> 06:39.960
You are adding spatial dimensions to a coordinate system.

06:39.960 --> 06:44.200
Oh, wow. So it's not a bucket getting full. It's a map getting more complex.

06:44.340 --> 06:50.640
Exactly. And let's delve into the specific mathematical setting Flyxion introduces to describe this,

06:50.860 --> 06:53.840
which is termed the RSVP field space.

06:54.240 --> 06:55.420
RSVP field space?

06:55.540 --> 07:01.760
Yes. If we sort of shift our visual backdrop here to this sprawling interconnected cityscape,

07:02.200 --> 07:04.780
we can visualize how this space operates.

07:04.940 --> 07:06.160
Okay, I can picture that.

07:06.160 --> 07:12.380
In this framework, any state of knowledge or memory is defined by a configuration of three specific mesters.

07:13.120 --> 07:16.240
Scalar density, vector flow, and entropy density.

07:16.580 --> 07:18.940
Okay, we definitely need to break those three down.

07:19.320 --> 07:21.960
Let's start with the first one, scalar density.

07:22.400 --> 07:28.740
Right. So scalar density represents the raw concentration of discrete facts or events

07:28.740 --> 07:31.660
in a given local area of your memory.

07:31.820 --> 07:32.480
Just the facts.

07:32.480 --> 07:37.960
Exactly. The raw data points. So, if you are learning a new language,

07:38.360 --> 07:42.440
the scalar density is the sheer number of vocabulary words you've encountered.

07:42.660 --> 07:45.520
Okay. Got it. Just the raw nodes on the map.

07:45.980 --> 07:47.980
What about the second one, vector flow?

07:48.520 --> 07:52.820
Well, a vector, mathematically speaking, has direction and magnitude.

07:52.820 --> 08:02.800
In the RSVP field space, the vector flow represents the directional, causal, and logical connections between those facts.

08:02.880 --> 08:05.080
Oh, okay. So, it's not just knowing words.

08:05.220 --> 08:08.340
Right. It's not just that you know the word apple and the word tree.

08:08.780 --> 08:14.420
It's the flow of understanding that apples grow on trees and drop from trees to gravity.

08:14.700 --> 08:15.200
I see.

08:15.200 --> 08:19.040
The vector flow is what gives the space its dynamic structure.

08:19.160 --> 08:25.920
Okay. So, the facts and the arrows pointing between the facts. That makes sense. That leaves the third one, entropy density.

08:25.960 --> 08:27.000
Yes. Entropy density.

08:27.300 --> 08:32.740
Now, in thermodynamics, entropy is usually like chaos or disorder, right?

08:32.740 --> 08:36.180
Right. How does that fit into the geometry of learning?

08:37.020 --> 08:51.740
It's a great question. In this specific topological context, entropy density refers to the amount of flexibility, the available volume, or you could say the wiggle room within a given arrangement of facts.

08:51.820 --> 08:53.300
Wiggle room. I like that.

08:53.300 --> 09:03.700
Yeah. It is a measure of how many slightly different valid configurations exist that still satisfy the exact same logical constraints.

09:03.880 --> 09:06.800
Ah. So, you're not locked into just one way of thinking.

09:07.020 --> 09:16.920
Exactly. High entropy density means your understanding isn't brittle. You have a lot of conceptual space to maneuver without actually violating any of the core facts.

09:16.920 --> 09:28.100
Okay. So, let me summarize. The RSVP field space is essentially the landscape built out of the facts, the connections between those facts, and the flexibility around them.

09:28.160 --> 09:35.580
Yes. Perfectly stated. Within this geometric space, Flyxion identifies three distinct regimes of learning.

09:35.700 --> 09:36.780
Okay. Three regimes.

09:37.040 --> 09:43.740
And the boundaries between these regimes dictate everything about how a system behaves. The first is the constrained regime.

09:44.020 --> 09:44.500
Constrained.

09:44.500 --> 09:46.460
This is an over-determined state.

09:46.460 --> 09:53.220
Over-determined meaning, you have more rules and data points than you have space to put them, right?

09:53.340 --> 09:53.740
Exactly.

09:54.000 --> 10:03.440
It's like trying to pack for a month-long trip into a tiny carry-on suitcase. You simply do not have the spatial dimensions to fit the data.

10:03.920 --> 10:06.820
That is a highly accurate way to visualize it, yeah.

10:06.960 --> 10:07.180
Yeah.

10:07.920 --> 10:11.380
Mathematically, the constraints outnumber your degrees of freedom.

10:11.580 --> 10:12.040
Right.

10:12.040 --> 10:18.660
In statistics and early machine learning, this is where the classic bias-variance trade-off lives.

10:19.200 --> 10:25.200
Because your model is too simple, your suitcase is too small, you are forced to throw things out.

10:25.280 --> 10:26.620
You literally have to.

10:26.660 --> 10:32.200
You must compress the data, prioritize certain features, ignore others.

10:32.200 --> 10:35.780
You develop a high bias just to make the data fit.

10:36.140 --> 10:36.580
Wow.

10:36.920 --> 10:41.840
And this regime is the entire basis for the bottleneck assumption we talked about earlier.

10:42.100 --> 10:45.760
We assumed the brain was permanently stuck in this carry-on suitcase.

10:46.000 --> 10:46.200
Right.

10:46.280 --> 10:50.740
Because we thought the data of the real world was infinite and our neurons were finite.

10:50.960 --> 10:53.140
We thought we were always packing a carry-on.

10:53.340 --> 10:53.780
Precisely.

10:53.780 --> 10:55.340
Okay, so what is the second regime?

10:55.820 --> 10:57.600
The second is the sufficient regime.

10:58.480 --> 11:08.740
This occurs when you increase the system's capacity just enough so that the number of degrees of freedom exactly matches the number of constraints.

11:09.540 --> 11:10.020
Oh.

11:10.340 --> 11:13.200
Okay, so the suitcase is exactly the size of the clothes.

11:13.480 --> 11:13.800
Yes.

11:14.000 --> 11:16.820
But imagine the clothes are made of rigid plastic.

11:17.600 --> 11:18.080
Oh.

11:18.080 --> 11:22.960
In the sufficient regime, you manage to fit the exact data perfectly.

11:23.600 --> 11:25.220
The error drops to zero.

11:25.860 --> 11:30.220
But the geometric solutions are just these isolated discrete points.

11:30.480 --> 11:33.620
So there is absolutely no wiggle room.

11:33.780 --> 11:34.200
None.

11:34.560 --> 11:35.840
Zero entropy density.

11:36.440 --> 11:39.620
The system is perfectly accurate, but it's incredibly brittle.

11:39.820 --> 11:41.280
So if anything changes...

11:41.280 --> 11:41.480
Right.

11:41.480 --> 11:49.800
If a new, slightly unexpected data point arrives, the entire configuration shatters because there is no flexibility to absorb it.

11:49.920 --> 11:51.700
That sounds incredibly stressful.

11:51.840 --> 11:52.300
It is.

11:52.840 --> 11:59.920
But then, as you continue to expand the system's capacity, you cross a critical threshold into the third regime.

12:00.480 --> 12:01.640
The excess regime.

12:01.640 --> 12:05.120
And this is where the whole paradigm flips upside down, isn't it?

12:05.120 --> 12:05.720
Oh, completely.

12:05.960 --> 12:07.100
This is the end of compression.

12:07.100 --> 12:12.060
In the excess regime, your degrees of freedom vastly outnumber your constraints.

12:12.260 --> 12:14.120
You have way more space than you need.

12:14.240 --> 12:14.380
Yep.

12:14.640 --> 12:15.080
Exactly.

12:15.520 --> 12:23.340
You have exponentially more parameters, more structural dimensions than the specific problem strictly requires.

12:23.600 --> 12:31.920
I really want to highlight this for you listening because this is where the paper just dismantles decades of cognitive science.

12:31.980 --> 12:32.740
It really does.

12:32.740 --> 12:40.200
Because the old assumption was that if you have too much capacity, if you memorize the data perfectly, you fail to generalize.

12:40.280 --> 12:43.060
You just become a rote memorization machine.

12:43.280 --> 12:43.580
Yes.

12:44.000 --> 12:45.420
The fear of overfitting.

12:45.660 --> 12:45.880
Right.

12:46.420 --> 12:49.160
But Flickshan says the complete opposite happens.

12:49.420 --> 12:53.260
In the excess regime, the system perfectly memorizes the data.

12:53.840 --> 12:59.160
It forms an exact fit to the facts, but it continues to extrapolate sensibly.

12:59.160 --> 13:04.620
Because it creates a massive, high-dimensional manifold of possibilities.

13:04.800 --> 13:05.340
A manifold.

13:05.840 --> 13:12.240
Yeah, a manifold is basically just a topological space that locally resembles flat Euclidean space.

13:12.460 --> 13:12.800
Okay.

13:13.220 --> 13:19.420
Because you have so many excess dimensions, the system doesn't have to compress the facts to make them fit.

13:20.120 --> 13:26.760
It just arranges them in a higher-dimensional geometry where they naturally sit without contradicting each other.

13:26.760 --> 13:31.520
It's like moving out of the carry-on suitcase and into a massive industrial warehouse.

13:31.720 --> 13:32.240
I love that.

13:32.520 --> 13:32.700
Yeah.

13:32.820 --> 13:37.760
Because when you are in the constrained suitcase, a new box is a crisis.

13:38.080 --> 13:39.840
You have to crush it to make it fit.

13:39.980 --> 13:40.220
Right.

13:40.760 --> 13:46.600
But when you move into the excess warehouse, bringing in a new box actually helps you.

13:46.980 --> 13:48.740
The new box isn't a burden.

13:48.740 --> 13:53.580
It acts as like a support pillar to help you build the architecture of the shelving.

13:54.420 --> 13:56.940
You are building the geometry as you go.

13:57.460 --> 14:03.020
That structural framing is exactly why the master builder isn't overwhelmed by the wire.

14:03.980 --> 14:08.480
They have an excess of dimensions to place that new data point into.

14:08.700 --> 14:10.020
They already have the warehouse.

14:10.600 --> 14:11.260
Exactly.

14:11.700 --> 14:13.000
Compression isn't happening.

14:13.120 --> 14:16.900
The system is just navigating a vast space of possibilities.

14:16.900 --> 14:21.200
You know, this sheds so much light on a phenomenon I see all the time.

14:21.440 --> 14:26.000
Think about a student who is grinding away studying for a brutal exam.

14:26.240 --> 14:26.540
Okay.

14:26.660 --> 14:27.480
They hit a wall.

14:27.740 --> 14:33.080
They feel completely saturated, brain dead, and they suddenly find themselves deep down

14:33.080 --> 14:38.900
a Wikipedia rabbit hole reading about, like, the construction techniques of Roman aqueducts.

14:39.500 --> 14:39.680
Right.

14:39.760 --> 14:40.560
Totally unrelated.

14:41.240 --> 14:45.800
Historically, a teacher would call that a failure of focus, a distraction.

14:45.800 --> 14:51.640
The student's hard drive got full, so they crashed and started doing something useless.

14:52.140 --> 14:59.040
But under Flyxion's RSVP framework, that is an entirely rational structural behavior.

14:59.280 --> 14:59.600
Right.

14:59.940 --> 15:02.620
The paper calls it coordinate frame rotation.

15:03.140 --> 15:03.420
Yes.

15:03.800 --> 15:06.900
The student's mind isn't a hard drive that got full.

15:07.140 --> 15:09.020
It's a geometric map.

15:09.020 --> 15:14.300
They exhausted the specific local dimensions of whatever subject they were studying.

15:15.020 --> 15:17.300
They hit a local constrained state.

15:17.640 --> 15:19.380
A bottleneck in that specific area.

15:19.580 --> 15:20.000
Exactly.

15:20.360 --> 15:26.500
So, to keep the overall system active without burning out that local patch, the brain spontaneously

15:26.500 --> 15:30.020
rotates its coordinate frame into a totally different dimension.

15:30.360 --> 15:36.480
It starts learning about aqueducts to maintain the flow of learning without overloading the local

15:36.480 --> 15:37.080
constraints.

15:37.080 --> 15:38.800
They're just navigating the warehouse.

15:38.960 --> 15:39.580
They aren't failing.

15:39.840 --> 15:40.460
Not at all.

15:40.920 --> 15:47.940
But this navigability introduces a profound secondary problem, which brings us to the next

15:47.940 --> 15:49.440
major mechanism in the paper.

15:49.600 --> 15:49.840
Okay.

15:49.880 --> 15:50.540
What's the problem?

15:50.700 --> 15:57.640
If you are in this massive warehouse and you have millions of excess dimensions, that means

15:57.640 --> 16:02.360
there are virtually infinite different ways to correctly organize the data.

16:02.580 --> 16:02.980
Right.

16:02.980 --> 16:08.500
There are infinite configurations that technically satisfy the exact same constraints.

16:08.940 --> 16:09.480
Oh, I see.

16:09.660 --> 16:17.060
So, if I have a million ways to correctly interpret a set of facts, how do I decide where to actually

16:17.060 --> 16:17.740
settle down?

16:17.840 --> 16:19.740
How do I form a stable worldview?

16:20.040 --> 16:20.300
Yes.

16:21.120 --> 16:25.700
To answer that, Flyxion introduces a concept called projected gradient flow.

16:25.700 --> 16:29.840
And it's guided by what is termed a soft action functional.

16:30.440 --> 16:30.760
Okay.

16:30.880 --> 16:31.900
Soft action functional.

16:32.080 --> 16:34.020
Let's define the action functional part.

16:34.220 --> 16:38.940
In physics, when we talk about action, we're usually talking about the path of least resistance,

16:39.200 --> 16:39.360
right?

16:39.580 --> 16:43.160
Like light bending through water to take the quickest path.

16:43.160 --> 16:44.000
Precisely.

16:44.640 --> 16:46.480
The principle of stationary action.

16:47.380 --> 16:53.280
A soft action functional in this context is a secondary set of preferences, often called

16:53.280 --> 16:54.560
inductive biases.

16:54.860 --> 16:55.820
Inductive biases.

16:55.900 --> 16:56.120
Okay.

16:56.300 --> 16:56.480
Yeah.

16:56.980 --> 17:02.400
These guide the system when the hard facts alone aren't enough to narrow down a single answer.

17:02.400 --> 17:07.580
It is essentially the system's inherent tendency to seek stability.

17:08.080 --> 17:13.380
And the dynamics of how it searches for this stability occur in two very distinct phases.

17:14.200 --> 17:20.660
These are most visible in a discrete event calculus that Flyxion outlines, affectionately named

17:20.660 --> 17:21.560
sphere pop.

17:21.920 --> 17:23.000
Sphere pop.

17:23.120 --> 17:23.800
I love that.

17:23.860 --> 17:27.400
It sounds like a candy, but we are actually talking about discrete calculus.

17:27.860 --> 17:28.680
Indeed we are.

17:28.680 --> 17:34.520
Sphere pop deals with how the system reacts the exact millisecond a new event occurs.

17:35.060 --> 17:37.540
A new fact enters the RSVP space.

17:38.040 --> 17:40.660
The system must immediately process it.

17:40.880 --> 17:41.060
Right.

17:41.300 --> 17:42.680
And it does this in two phases.

17:43.300 --> 17:46.080
The normal snap and the tangential drift.

17:46.220 --> 17:46.440
Okay.

17:46.520 --> 17:47.600
Let's look at the first phase.

17:47.740 --> 17:48.640
The normal snap.

17:48.760 --> 17:51.220
The normal snap is practically instantaneous.

17:52.200 --> 17:55.000
Mathematically, it is a rapid projection operator.

17:55.220 --> 17:56.060
A projection.

17:56.300 --> 17:56.500
Yes.

17:56.500 --> 18:01.500
A projection in linear algebra maps a vector onto a specific subspace.

18:02.120 --> 18:07.840
Here, the system instantly projects its current state onto what is called the admissible set

18:07.840 --> 18:11.540
to enforce strict logical consistency with the new fact.

18:11.540 --> 18:18.400
So, a new piece of data arrives and the system violently snaps to a configuration that does not

18:18.400 --> 18:19.680
violate that new fact.

18:19.780 --> 18:20.200
Exactly.

18:20.200 --> 18:23.640
It prioritizes immediate logical truth.

18:24.140 --> 18:24.440
Yes.

18:25.260 --> 18:29.600
It ensures the system is technically correct according to the event log.

18:30.020 --> 18:33.200
It's a highly elastic, rigid response.

18:34.080 --> 18:36.820
So, what does this all mean in the real world?

18:37.560 --> 18:39.980
Let me try to visualize this in physical terms.

18:40.200 --> 18:40.720
Go for it.

18:40.720 --> 18:43.640
The normal snap is a pure reflex.

18:44.360 --> 18:48.080
Imagine we are standing in a kitchen and someone knocks a glass off the counter.

18:48.580 --> 18:54.420
Before you even consciously process it, your arm darts out and you catch the glass midair.

18:54.640 --> 18:54.940
Right.

18:55.280 --> 18:56.680
That is the normal snap.

18:57.060 --> 19:01.900
You instantly projected your body into a state that satisfied the new constraint.

19:02.340 --> 19:04.560
The glass must not hit the floor.

19:04.560 --> 19:07.560
That captures the elastic immediacy of it perfectly.

19:07.720 --> 19:07.860
Right.

19:07.960 --> 19:09.140
The glass didn't break.

19:09.340 --> 19:10.560
You are technically successful.

19:11.340 --> 19:13.560
You are truthful to the demands of the event.

19:14.220 --> 19:21.400
But, if you just freeze there, like holding the glass awkwardly down by your shins with your back

19:21.400 --> 19:25.420
completely twisted, you are in a highly unstable geometry.

19:25.940 --> 19:30.100
Mathematically speaking, you are in a region of extreme high curvature.

19:30.460 --> 19:30.780
Right.

19:31.060 --> 19:32.720
My muscles are going to start cramping.

19:32.720 --> 19:38.200
I'm technically holding the glass, but the slightest perturbation, a dog brushing against

19:38.200 --> 19:41.980
my leg, or just the passage of time in my system, will fail.

19:42.340 --> 19:42.980
You'll drop it.

19:43.040 --> 19:44.180
I'll drop the glass anyway.

19:44.920 --> 19:48.080
Being purely correct is physically unsustainable.

19:48.360 --> 19:51.900
Which is exactly why the system must initiate the second phase.

19:52.720 --> 19:53.580
Tangential drift.

19:53.680 --> 19:54.700
Tangential drift.

19:54.820 --> 19:55.080
Okay.

