Well, we are sliding around the RSVP space looking for the biggest couch, feeling the boundaries

23:55.380 --> 23:57.020
of the room to guide our drift.

23:57.180 --> 23:57.520
Right.

23:57.520 --> 24:02.540
But, what happens if the room itself was built by a madman?

24:02.980 --> 24:07.780
What happens if the architectural constraints of the space are fundamentally broken?

24:08.300 --> 24:13.380
Oh, you have just hit upon the central pivot of the entire paper.

24:13.480 --> 24:14.440
I knew it.

24:14.440 --> 24:19.480
Everything we have discussed so far assumes the underlying data can actually be resolved

24:19.480 --> 24:21.020
into a smooth manifold.

24:21.940 --> 24:27.920
Flyxion's primary thesis investigates what occurs when the event log itself cannot support

24:27.920 --> 24:29.100
a coherent structure.

24:29.480 --> 24:29.760
Okay.

24:29.980 --> 24:34.600
To understand this, we have to establish the physical properties of the walls of that room

24:34.600 --> 24:35.120
you mentioned.

24:36.000 --> 24:39.880
Flyxion defines these walls through a principle called log sovereignty.

24:40.420 --> 24:41.460
Log sovereignty.

24:41.700 --> 24:43.240
The absolute rule of the past.

24:43.240 --> 24:44.020
Precisely.

24:44.600 --> 24:51.020
In this geometric framework, the event log, the chronological data set of everything the

24:51.020 --> 24:54.560
system has experienced, is not treated as compressible data.

24:54.720 --> 24:55.320
It's not.

24:55.480 --> 24:55.700
No.

24:56.000 --> 24:58.900
It is a rigid physical boundary condition.

24:59.020 --> 25:04.140
So, my memory of what happened yesterday isn't just a file I can edit or compress to save

25:04.140 --> 25:04.640
space.

25:04.820 --> 25:10.400
It is the actual structural architecture of the RSVP space I am moving through today.

25:10.460 --> 25:10.840
Yes.

25:11.520 --> 25:12.300
It is the wall.

25:12.300 --> 25:19.780
And Flyxion grounds this mathematically in thermodynamics, specifically invoking Landauer's

25:19.780 --> 25:20.160
principle.

25:20.360 --> 25:21.320
Landauer's principle.

25:21.320 --> 25:24.480
This is a foundational concept from the 1960s, right?

25:24.720 --> 25:26.360
Rolf Landauer at IBM.

25:26.560 --> 25:26.860
That's right.

25:27.200 --> 25:31.760
Landauer's principle bridged the gap between information theory and thermodynamics.

25:31.760 --> 25:37.240
It essentially states that the erasure of information is a dissipative process.

25:37.240 --> 25:40.120
Dissipative meaning it loses energy.

25:40.120 --> 25:41.120
Yes.

25:41.120 --> 25:45.600
It is the only truly irreversible computational operation.

25:45.600 --> 25:51.740
Simply moving data around or calculating a reversible function theoretically doesn't have

25:51.740 --> 25:52.740
to consume energy.

25:52.740 --> 26:01.020
But deleting a bit of information, resetting a one to a zero, and forever losing the previous

26:01.020 --> 26:06.400
state that mandatorily increases the thermodynamic entropy of the environment.

26:06.400 --> 26:09.180
It costs physical energy and generates heat.

26:09.180 --> 26:09.780
Exactly.

26:09.780 --> 26:10.720
Yeah.

26:10.720 --> 26:17.520
Therefore, under the strict mathematical boundaries of log sovereignty, the system never deletes

26:17.520 --> 26:18.220
the past.

26:19.000 --> 26:22.820
Erasure is energetically forbidden within the natural gradient flow.

26:23.000 --> 26:24.080
Never deletes it.

26:24.080 --> 26:24.440
Never.

26:25.380 --> 26:28.140
The log does not merely describe the state of the system.

26:28.500 --> 26:30.940
It restricts the space of possible states.

26:31.420 --> 26:32.920
It is a boundary operator.

26:33.100 --> 26:33.360
Okay.

26:33.980 --> 26:36.800
This gives rise to the rule of historical closure.

26:37.520 --> 26:42.960
The dynamics of your learning, your normal snaps, and your tangential drifts must remain

26:42.960 --> 26:46.660
entirely within the boundaries of the event log at all times.

26:46.820 --> 26:51.520
Let me process this because the implications for human psychology here are just staggering.

26:51.820 --> 26:52.500
They really are.

26:52.500 --> 26:56.540
Think about your own lived experience, the things you have witnessed, the events that

26:56.540 --> 26:57.220
have shaped you.

26:57.720 --> 27:03.260
If you go through something contradictory or painful, and your strategy is to try and delete

27:03.260 --> 27:03.440
it...

27:03.440 --> 27:04.240
To suppress it.

27:04.400 --> 27:04.680
Right.

27:04.820 --> 27:07.020
To pretend the event simply did not occur.

27:07.600 --> 27:10.100
You are actively violating log sovereignty.

27:10.380 --> 27:13.540
You are attempting an energetically impossible operation.

27:13.820 --> 27:14.180
Right.

27:14.620 --> 27:19.140
The past isn't a digital file you can drag to the trash bin to free up memory.

27:19.140 --> 27:24.880
It is the physical geometric walls of the maze you are currently walking through.

27:25.360 --> 27:25.420
Yes.

27:26.140 --> 27:30.700
You can't just decide to walk through a concrete wall because you want to forget it exists.

27:30.900 --> 27:32.420
The wall is sovereign.

27:32.760 --> 27:34.280
It is a profound realization.

27:35.400 --> 27:38.540
You are permanently bound by the geometry of your own history.

27:38.540 --> 27:42.640
But, this brings us to the terrifying part.

27:42.700 --> 27:42.940
Yes.

27:43.460 --> 27:49.520
If the log forms the walls of our reality, and we are energetically forbidden from ever

27:49.520 --> 27:55.800
deleting a wall, what happens when the log itself contains irreconcilable contradictions?

27:56.080 --> 27:57.220
That is the big question.

27:57.220 --> 28:02.980
What if event A says a wall is solidly right here, and event B, which is also sovereign

28:02.980 --> 28:07.300
and undeletable, says the exact same wall is three feet to the left?

28:07.400 --> 28:11.520
Then the system has encountered a structural impossibility.

28:12.060 --> 28:14.740
And, we have arrived at the namesake of the paper.

28:14.860 --> 28:16.840
This is the exact definition of error.

28:17.260 --> 28:19.160
Here's where it gets really interesting.

28:19.160 --> 28:24.020
When we hear the word error, we naturally think of a mistake.

28:24.520 --> 28:28.440
We think of a typo, or getting a math problem wrong.

28:29.040 --> 28:31.640
But Flyxion redefines error entirely.

28:31.800 --> 28:32.120
Okay.

28:32.440 --> 28:36.220
In this framework, an error is not a scalar distance.

28:36.760 --> 28:40.300
It is not, you guessed five, but the true answer was seven.

28:40.400 --> 28:40.740
Right.

28:41.060 --> 28:44.740
That is merely a mismeasurement within a coherent space.

28:45.260 --> 28:48.920
A true error is a cohomological obstruction.

28:49.160 --> 28:50.960
Okay, cohomological obstruction.

28:51.340 --> 28:54.480
We are officially in the deep end of the topological pool.

28:54.820 --> 28:56.980
We definitely need to dissect this carefully.

28:57.560 --> 28:59.020
Let's start with cohomology.

28:59.580 --> 29:05.240
To understand cohomology in this context, we need to look at how this system builds its reality.

29:05.720 --> 29:11.660
The system attempts to create what is called a constraint sheaf out of its local experiences.

29:11.920 --> 29:13.720
A sheaf, like a bundle of wheat.

29:14.120 --> 29:15.500
Somewhat similar in concept.

29:15.500 --> 29:24.200
In topology, a sheaf is a tool for systematically tracking locally defined data attached to the open sets of a topological space.

29:24.320 --> 29:25.560
Okay, let's make that concrete.

29:25.680 --> 29:30.960
Imagine your entire history is divided into thousands of overlapping local patches.

29:31.340 --> 29:39.540
A patch might be a specific context, like how gravity works in my kitchen, or how my boss behaves on Tuesdays.

29:39.540 --> 29:43.940
Okay, so I have a massive patchwork quilt of local contexts.

29:44.200 --> 29:44.700
Exactly.

29:45.560 --> 29:53.040
Now, within any single local patch, the system can usually find a perfectly truthful, comfortable arrangement.

29:53.580 --> 29:54.880
A local truth.

29:54.880 --> 30:03.480
Right, the normal snap and tangential drift work perfectly to find a flat, stable geometry for that one specific patch.

30:03.580 --> 30:03.880
Yes.

30:04.380 --> 30:10.300
But for the system as a whole to be stable, it requires what is called a global section.

30:10.580 --> 30:13.940
Meaning all the local patches have to be stitched together perfectly.

30:14.160 --> 30:19.880
Stitched together without any gaps, and crucially, without any contradictions where they overlap.

30:19.880 --> 30:27.100
If patch A overlaps with patch B, the geometric facts in the overlapping region must completely agree.

30:27.220 --> 30:27.700
Makes sense.

30:28.020 --> 30:34.740
If my kitchen patch says water boils, and my living room patch says water boils, the overlap in the hallway is consistent.

30:35.000 --> 30:37.320
But this is where etch-co-homology comes in.

30:37.420 --> 30:38.500
Etch-co-homology.

30:38.940 --> 30:39.280
Yes.

30:39.720 --> 30:46.020
Each co-homology is a mathematical way to calculate whether a collection of locally consistent patches

30:46.020 --> 30:49.140
can actually be glued together into a global whole.

30:50.040 --> 30:53.340
It specifically calculates the differences on the overlaps.

30:53.400 --> 30:54.300
How does it do that?

30:54.580 --> 30:56.400
It forms an etch complex.

30:56.880 --> 30:58.040
It looks at the intersections.

30:58.740 --> 31:00.480
So say you have patch A, B, and C.

31:00.660 --> 31:00.920
Okay.

31:01.060 --> 31:02.580
A and B overlap and agree.

31:03.040 --> 31:04.420
B and C overlap and agree.

31:04.900 --> 31:06.300
C and A overlap and agree.

31:06.300 --> 31:07.300
So far, so good.

31:07.740 --> 31:14.180
But what happens right in the center where A, B, and C all intersect simultaneously?

31:14.180 --> 31:22.040
If the mathematical sum of their localized agreements does not equal zero, if there's a discrepancy

31:22.040 --> 31:26.280
when the loop closes, the co-homology class is non-trivial.

31:26.700 --> 31:29.420
Non-trivial, meaning there is a hole in the space.

31:29.640 --> 31:29.940
Yes.

31:30.720 --> 31:36.480
It mathematically proves that your locally consistent constraints absolutely cannot be glued into

31:36.480 --> 31:38.200
any smooth global configuration.

31:38.800 --> 31:39.320
Wow.

31:39.320 --> 31:45.820
It is not just difficult, it is structurally, topologically impossible in that number of

31:45.820 --> 31:46.220
dimensions.

31:46.380 --> 31:46.780
Okay, wait.

31:47.100 --> 31:48.420
Let's ground this for the listener.

31:48.880 --> 31:53.880
An M.C. Escher drawing is the perfect visual for a non-trivial co-homology class.

31:53.940 --> 31:54.440
Yes, it is.

31:54.800 --> 32:01.040
Think about the Penrose stairs, that famous drawing of the monks walking continuously upward

32:01.040 --> 32:02.360
in a closed loop.

32:02.360 --> 32:10.260
The Penrose stairs are an exact, literal manifestation of a co-homological obstruction.

32:11.040 --> 32:16.080
Because if you take a piece of paper and cover up the whole drawing except for one single

32:16.080 --> 32:19.220
corner of the staircase, it makes perfect sense.

32:19.340 --> 32:19.500
Right.

32:19.660 --> 32:23.500
One step is higher than the previous one, gravity points down.

32:23.820 --> 32:27.040
It is a perfectly locally consistent patch.

32:27.220 --> 32:30.760
You could build that one corner out of wood in your garage.

32:30.760 --> 32:34.140
Yes, the local sheaf is perfectly admissible.

32:34.140 --> 32:40.260
But if you try to take those four perfectly logical, locally consistent corners and glue

32:40.260 --> 32:44.980
them together in 3D space, you hit a topological impossibility.

32:45.260 --> 32:47.440
The math of the overlaps fails.

32:47.800 --> 32:53.780
The last step cannot simultaneously be higher than the previous step A and D be the bottom

32:53.780 --> 32:55.180
step of the first corner.

32:55.400 --> 32:58.880
The history of the drawing contradicts itself when the loop closes.

32:58.880 --> 33:03.100
That is the essence of Flyxion-stability-obstruction dichotomy.

33:03.720 --> 33:09.780
You either have a smooth, stable worldview where the global section exists, a trivial co-homology

33:09.780 --> 33:14.280
class, or you have a topological tear, a non-trivial class.

33:14.340 --> 33:15.260
And there's no in-between.

33:15.720 --> 33:17.740
There is absolutely no middle ground.

33:17.840 --> 33:21.200
You can't have an almost coherent Escher staircase.

33:21.200 --> 33:22.020
You cannot.

33:22.580 --> 33:29.740
It either closes perfectly in 3D space or it represents a fundamental tear in the medium

33:29.740 --> 33:30.440
of reality.

33:31.120 --> 33:33.460
And this is a massive paradigm shift.

33:33.580 --> 33:34.380
It really is.

33:34.500 --> 33:36.480
It means the system didn't make a mistake.

33:37.280 --> 33:43.360
The system is faithfully reporting the data of the event log, but the event log itself dictates

33:43.360 --> 33:44.940
a space that cannot exist.

33:44.940 --> 33:45.660
Wow.

33:46.540 --> 33:55.000
If error isn't a bad guess, but an actual structural pair in the fabric of our experience, how does

33:55.000 --> 33:57.860
a system behave when it walks right into one?

33:57.940 --> 34:05.020
Like, if our cognitive map is an Escher drawing, how do we physically experience that obstruction?

34:05.560 --> 34:08.140
That brings us to the physical diagnosis of the error.

34:08.140 --> 34:14.120
When a system's gradient flow hits this kind of degenerate geometry, it experiences what

34:14.120 --> 34:16.820
Flyxion terms viscoelastic failure.

34:17.460 --> 34:18.060
Viscoelastic.

34:18.360 --> 34:23.280
So displaying properties of both viscosity, like thick honey, and the elasticity, like a

34:23.280 --> 34:23.860
rubber band.

34:24.100 --> 34:24.540
Exactly.

34:25.380 --> 34:28.040
Recall the two phases of sphere pop we discussed earlier.

